+{"id":"frankenpandas-cco1r","title":"fd90.105: README selection example uses df.loc(str) + df.loc_rows() — both wrong arg type / non-existent fn","description":"fd90.74-104 README audit. Lines 1484-1485 in Selection and Indexing show:

  let row = df.loc("row_label")?;           // Single row by label
  let subset = df.loc_rows(&["a", "b"])?;   // Multiple rows

Both lines wouldn't compile:
1. df.loc takes &[IndexLabel] (a slice of labels), NOT a single &str. Verified at crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:17168 — pub fn loc(&self, labels: &[IndexLabel]).
2. df.loc_rows does not exist. grep -rnE 'fn loc_rows' crates/ returns nothing. Only loc, loc_with_columns, iloc_rows (private).

The README's separation between 'single row' and 'multiple rows' methods is also fictional — there's only one loc() that takes a slice. Both single-row and multi-row calls go through the same function.

Fix: rewrite the two-line block as a single example using the actual loc(&[IndexLabel]) signature with the From<&str> blanket via .into(). Pure README change.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T10:16:01.624887293Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T10:17:46.585781205Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T10:17:46.583133569Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
